  "text": "_G.R. Bhat et al. Results in Control and Optimization 14 (2024) 100401_ of standards for operating them. A difference in drone aviation standards is observed through countries and states [3]. The difference in these standards is caused due to several factors such as terrain, infrastructure, and altitude. These standards decide factors such as maximum flying altitude, frequency of operation, etc., and directly impact the drone’s weight, materials, hardware, and software. Fig. 1 shows a visual representation of the regulations in a few major countries promoting research in the area of drones. Today, the application in addition use of drones is increasing rapidly [1]. Besides commercial purposes, UAVs are designed according to various applications such as agriculture, archaeological research, education, civil surveys, and defence [2]. However, they require a set of standards for operating them. A difference in drone aviation standards is observed through countries and states [3]. The difference in these standards is caused due to several factors such as terrain, infrastructure, and altitude. These standards decide factors such as maximum flying altitude, frequency of operation, etc., and directly impact the drone’s weight, materials, hardware, and software [4]. Fig. 1 shows a visual representation of the regulations in a few major countries promoting research in the field of drones. Baassi et al. [5] stated that the operating height and weight factors discussed in Fig. 1 affect aerial locomotion. Global standardization of aviation rules and regulations is a challenge. Drones require a license to fly and require a pilot to have a license to operate. At times, drone operators require permission to fly drones on private property. These laws are introduced to avoid often happening accidents in flight, both in the military and commercial UAVs [6]. These challenges are addressed by implementing closed-loop control systems on various drone components [7]. Automated drones are possible due to closed-loop control systems. An autonomous flight is possible due to automated individual parts of drones. The key purpose of an autonomous drone is to lessen human input and error through the help of Machine Learning (ML) and Artificial Intelligence (AI) [8]. Carev, et al. [9], invented a universal metric to measure research programs, planning innovative programs, and comparing efforts to develop autonomous control technology. This metric is known as the Autonomous Control Level (ACL) for a UAV. The ACL metric system was made by Air Force Research Laboratory’s Air Vehicles Directorate. Most UAVs today which",
